The Foreign Office has advised British citizens in Russia to consider leaving by any commercial routes available. ‘If your presence in Russia is not essential, we strongly advise that you consider leaving by remaining commercial routes,’ the FCDO said in a statement. The advice came as Russia announced it would be grounding most flights abroad from tomorrow. The FCDO has urged Brits not to travel to anywhere in Russia due to the lack of available flight options to return to the UK, and the increased volatility in the Russian economy. For the latest updates on the Russia-Ukraine war, visit our live blog:  Russia-Ukraine live Countries have imposed a barrage of sanctions on Russia after it invaded Ukraine 10 days ago. The nation is becoming increasingly isolated as it is frozen out of the global financial systems and businesses cut ties with it. Last week, the UK, EU, US and Canada closed their airspace to Russian planes, limiting flights in and out of the country. Moments after the FCDO published their advise, Russia announced it would be grounding most flights abroad from tomorrow. This is a breaking news story, more to follow soon… Check back shortly for further updates. Got a story? Get in touch with our news team by emailing us at webnews@metro.co.uk. Or you can submit your videos and pictures here. For more stories like this, check our news page. Follow Metro.co.uk on Twitter and Facebook for the latest news updates. You can now also get Metro.co.uk articles sent straight to your device. Sign up for our daily push alerts here. 